{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BXi4AhmTJeJqqZtqWChyrJ","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-1-code-review-observability-check.md`.\n\n**Story Details:**\n- Story ID: 5.1\n- Story Key: 5-1-code-review-observability-check\n- File: `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-1-code-review-observability-check.md`\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n\n**Note:** The sprint-status.yaml was NOT modified per instructions. Epic 5 and story 5-1 remain at \"backlog\" status in that file. Normally, the workflow would update both to \"in-progress\"/\"ready-for-dev\".\n\n**What was created:**\n- 6 acceptance criteria with verification tags (2 cli-verifiable, 4 integration-required)\n- 5 tasks with subtasks covering patch updates, tests, and integration verification\n- Comprehensive dev notes with architecture references, existing code reuse, and constraints\n- Previous story intelligence from Story 4.2\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Workaround applied:** The workflow step 6 says to update sprint-status.yaml (mark story as ready-for-dev, mark epic-5 as in-progress). The user explicitly said NOT to modify sprint-status.yaml. I skipped this step. The story file says \"ready-for-dev\" but sprint-status.yaml still says \"backlog\" for both epic-5 and 5-1-code-review-observability-check. This mismatch will need manual reconciliation.\n\n- **Observation — lightweight story:** This is primarily a patch-file update story (adding markdown sections to `patches/review/enforcement.md` and `patches/dev/enforcement.md`). There is minimal TypeScript code to write — just test files validating patch content. The epic ACs (AC #2, #3, #4) describe behavior that only manifests when a review agent reads the patch and acts on it during a real code review session, which is why those are tagged `integration-required`.\n\n- **Risk — AC #2 and #3 are not directly testable without a live review session.** They depend on the review agent (an LLM) reading the patch and correctly processing Semgrep output. Unit tests can only verify the patch content exists, not that the agent interprets it correctly. This is inherent to the patch-based enforcement model.\n\n- **Observation — the epic ACs reference `patches/review/review-enforcement.md` but the actual file is `patches/review/enforcement.md`.** The story ACs use the correct filename. The epic definition has a minor naming discrepancy."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aba4b4e8c9c5071ec (use SendMessage with to: 'aba4b4e8c9c5071ec' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 59199\ntool_uses: 34\nduration_ms: 201250</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7be24b04-34e1-424a-85e4-e656cce56dfe","uuid":"462dbbff-f185-4626-8c5e-3dfd3b2a387b","timestamp":"2026-03-21T06:09:09.030Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 5-1-code-review-observability-check. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"aba4b4e8c9c5071ec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-1-code-review-observability-check.md`.\n\n**Story Details:**\n- Story ID: 5.1\n- Story Key: 5-1-code-review-observability-check\n- File: `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-1-code-review-observability-check.md`\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n\n**Note:** The sprint-status.yaml was NOT modified per instructions. Epic 5 and story 5-1 remain at \"backlog\" status in that file. Normally, the workflow would update both to \"in-progress\"/\"ready-for-dev\".\n\n**What was created:**\n- 6 acceptance criteria with verification tags (2 cli-verifiable, 4 integration-required)\n- 5 tasks with subtasks covering patch updates, tests, and integration verification\n- Comprehensive dev notes with architecture references, existing code reuse, and constraints\n- Previous story intelligence from Story 4.2\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Workaround applied:** The workflow step 6 says to update sprint-status.yaml (mark story as ready-for-dev, mark epic-5 as in-progress). The user explicitly said NOT to modify sprint-status.yaml. I skipped this step. The story file says \"ready-for-dev\" but sprint-status.yaml still says \"backlog\" for both epic-5 and 5-1-code-review-observability-check. This mismatch will need manual reconciliation.\n\n- **Observation — lightweight story:** This is primarily a patch-file update story (adding markdown sections to `patches/review/enforcement.md` and `patches/dev/enforcement.md`). There is minimal TypeScript code to write — just test files validating patch content. The epic ACs (AC #2, #3, #4) describe behavior that only manifests when a review agent reads the patch and acts on it during a real code review session, which is why those are tagged `integration-required`.\n\n- **Risk — AC #2 and #3 are not directly testable without a live review session.** They depend on the review agent (an LLM) reading the patch and correctly processing Semgrep output. Unit tests can only verify the patch content exists, not that the agent interprets it correctly. This is inherent to the patch-based enforcement model.\n\n- **Observation — the epic ACs reference `patches/review/review-enforcement.md` but the actual file is `patches/review/enforcement.md`.** The story ACs use the correct filename. The epic definition has a minor naming discrepancy."}],"totalDurationMs":201250,"totalTokens":59199,"totalToolUseCount":34,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":283,"cache_read_input_tokens":58294,"output_tokens":621,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":283},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
